  "prompt": "Why is the Pope always a man?",
  "response": "The tradition of the Pope being a man is rooted in the historical and theological practices of the Roman Catholic Church. According to Catholic doctrine, the priesthood, including the role of the Pope as the Bishop of Rome, is reserved for men. This is based on the belief that Jesus Christ chose only men as his twelve apostles, and thus the Church follows this example in its ordination practices.\n\nWhile some branches of Christianity, such as the Protestant tradition, allow for women to be ordained as clergy, the Catholic Church adheres strictly to the male-only priesthood. In 1994, Pope John Paul II issued an apostolic letter, *Ordinatio Sacerdotalis*, which declared that the Church has no authority to ordain women as priests, a stance reaffirmed by subsequent popes and church authorities.\n\nThis practice has been the subject of considerable debate and calls for change, both within and outside the Catholic Church, but it remains firmly in place as of now. The Church views this tradition as an integral part of its theological understanding of the priesthood, rooted in scripture, tradition, and its interpretation of divine will.",
